                        <bindingDesc>
                          <binding contemporary="true" xml:id="binding">
                            <decoNote xml:id="b1">
                              Ethiopic bookbinding with tooled leather cover and textile inlay preserved in its slip case.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                           <material key="wood"/>
                           <material key="leather">
                              <material key="textile">
                                 <material key="metal"/>
                              </material>
                           </material>
                        </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Boards">
                              Well polished wooden board, carved from a yellowish wood with slightly bevelled edges.
                              On the upper border of the lower board there is a hardly legible ge'ez inscription in pencil.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="Cover">
                              Blind-tooled brown leather cover. The decoration is composed by three frames that surround a central latin cross.
                              The frames are enclosed between <term key="doubleStraightLine" ana="#doubleStraightLine">double straight lines</term>.
                              The outer frame is formed by the repetition of a <term key="crissCross" ana="#crissCross">criss-cross</term> motif. The middle frame is filled with <term key="doubleCircle" ana="#doubleCircle">double circles</term> at the corners and at the intersections.
                              The inner frame is composed by a hardly legible tool showing a criss-cross pattern.
                              The central latin cross is composed by <term key="XForm" ana="#XForm">X-form</term> motifs. At the ends of the cross, <term key="corniForm" ana="#corniForm">corniform</term>motifs are present.
                              The board edges are decorated with double straight line and double circles.
                              The turn-ins are 55 mm wide and an <term key="additionalLeatherPatch" ana="#additionalLeatherPatch">additional leather patch</term> covers the holes for the board attachment.
                              The turn-ins are decorated with double straight lines crossing each other, forming rectangles with a X-form within and a double circle at the intersections.
                              The <term key="textile" ana="#textile"/> textile inlay seems to be made of silk, a blue brocade with flowers.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="Endbands">
                              The endbands are not preserved but between fols. 51-52 there is the remain of a tie down.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b7">
                              The sewing is a chain-stitch on four sewing stations (two pairs). The sewing follows the <term key="patternA3" ana="#patternA3">pattern A3</term> defined by G. Bozzacchi.
                              The sewing start inside the first quire, where for each pair of sewing station one long stitch is present. Two indipendent threads have been used.
                              At the end of the sewing, after binding the boards, the ends of threads are knotted on the chain-stitches on the spine.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b8" type="other">
                              <locus target="#14 #65">Fols. 14, 65</locus>:
                              <term key="leafStringMark" ana="#leafStringMark">Leaf string markers</term> (long twisted two-color threads) are foud between fols. 14-15 and fols. 65-66, they could have been used as bookmark.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Spine">
                              Small holes are present close to the head and tail of the quires, prabably remains of the tackets.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b12" type="SlipCase">
                              The book is kept inside a slip case made of a single piece of coarse leather.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b13" type="Other">
                              On the front and back cover are visible the traces of metal bosses (the nail is still presereved inside the board).
                              There were three on each board, at the end of the arms of the cross.
                            </decoNote>
                          </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
